Caption: Happy #SlimeMoldSunday to Myxomycete lovers new and old! These amazing myxo fruiting bodies are Diachea leucopodia,Â one of my favorites because of theirÂ beautiful iridescence.Â  As with many slime molds, this species changes colors several times during its brief life cycle.Â  When they first arise from the white plasmodium, the fruiting bodies are white.Â  They then turn almost black, and as they mature and dry the peridium (outer covering of the spore-containing body) turns into these strikingly beautifulÂ iridescent blue, purple, and brown colors on a white stout stalk.Â  Although the individualÂ fruiting bodies are tiny, only 1-2mm tall, they can be easy to spot because they grow in dense and large clusters on leaves, grasses, and live and decaying plant material.Â  To see how tiny they are, see the second photo, which shows a few fruiting bodies on a twig with the tip of a fine point pen for scale. A little technical info for those of you who might be interested.Â  To photograph such tiny myxos with sharp detail, I use an extreme macro lens.Â  With such high magnifications, the depth of field (portion of the subject that is in sharp focus) is less than 0.05mm. To get a photo of the entire fruiting body in focus, I use a technique called focus stacking. My camera is mounted on a finely tuned rail, and the camera is moved in minuscule increments between each photo,Â so that the focal point changes with each photo.Â  Â For this photo, I took 138 individual images, which were then â€œstackedâ€ with specialized computer software that combines the most in-focus portions of each of the individual images into a composite image that shows everything in focus from front to back.

Date: 2022-08-02 05:09:43
Caption: Hexagonia tenuis fungi is plentiful in the regenerating native forests at the base of the escarpment. These areas were originally cleared for farmland and mining. The returning forests are only approximately 50 years into the process of establishing themselves again and I'm always in awe of their regenerative power. It's hard not to amorphosize natural phenomena with the constraints our language puts upon us. Fungi networks are described like the internet, beehives are described like officeworkers, but we know this is a crude way to narrate the complexity, abstraction, mystery and full expression of nature. So I tread tentatively knowing these words that follow are inept, but to experience a regenerating forest is to be part of a continual homecoming. With each species of native flora and fauna that returns I personally am exalted but there is no fanfare, fireworks or roll call within the forest itself. Instead a palatable gathering of strength and an emerging tranquillity spreads as each species reestablishes itself within the dynamics of the forest family. Many of the photos in this gallery are from this regenerating forest and it is a joy to share the homecoming of species like this fungi with you. #mycology #mycologysociety #fungus #mycologyphotography #fungilover #fungiphotography #fungifanatic #fantasticfungi #fungiofinstagram #fungiownunder #fungihunter #fungiaustralia #fungifreaks #fungihunting #fungiidentification #fungikingdom #fungilove #fungiphotography #fungioftheday #mushroom #mushrooms #mushlove #mushroomphotography #mushroomsofinstagram #australianfungi #fungi #forestbathing #forestfinds #naturesbeauty #forestlovers #biodiversity

Date: 2021-02-01 00:45:31
Caption: You might have read our recent post about the excessive use of damaging pesticides in imported cut flowers, but of almost equal concern is fungicide usage. You see, Ecuador, where many of the roses sold in the US are grown, has high amounts of rainfall and the greenhouses where these flowers are grown are notorious for holding in humidity and creating fungus issues like Botrytis. Botrytis can create spots on a rose, and often won't appear on a rose until after it's left the farm. To prevent these spots from showing up on roses once they hit the retail market and dissuading customers from buying them, foreign growers have developed a worrisome and toxic method of dipping the entire rose into a vat of fungicide, first dunking the bloom, and then the stem. The workers in charge of this job wear respirator masks to avoid inhaling the products, which are then packaged directly into flower sleeves and shipped to the US (no, they are not rinsed off afterward). Of the 37 products that are used as rose dip treatments, 17 of them have been identified by the Pesticide Action Network to be problematic as groundwater pollutants or harmful to humans, toxic to life and the environment. Unfortunately, Valentine's Day, the biggest flower holiday in the US, is also a time when domestic roses are, by and large, dormant in their fields. This means the VAST majority of cut roses purchased during February have been dipped in a toxic blend of fungicides and pesticides. Not exactly the way I'd want to say "I love you!" #flowers #colorado #coloradoflorist #farmerflorist #coloradofarmer #localflowers #pesticides #fungicides #toxicflowers #valentinesdayflowers #valentinesday #denver #denverflorist #roses #importedroses #buyamericangrown #americangrown #supportlocalflowers #supportamericanfarms #buyamericangrown #coloradogrown #freshcutcolorado #coloradoflowers

Caption: The brightly-coloured waxcaps are often thought of as the orchids of the fungi kingdom because they are so vibrant and showy, and also quite particular. They will only grow on undisturbed, nutrient-poor grasslands like ancient pasture and other land that has never been ploughed or fertilised. As a result, many species are rare and hard to find but some grow much closer to home â€“ literally. Waxcaps can appear in garden lawns, grassy churchyards and even the occasional cricket pitch as long as the conditions are right. Wherever you find them, their presence means youâ€™re in a very special place. Caption: Fomitopsis betulina EN This species is a saprotroph or parasite specific to Betula spp. It can be found on logs, dead trees, but sometimes in live trees too, although it possibly only infects already decaying, trees. Like other brown rot fungi it degrades the carbohydrate fraction of lignocellulose but, in contrast to white rot fungi, leaves lignin in the form of cubical brown fragments. Caption: Dendrocollybia racemosa - Branched shanklet Not my find but a collaborative effort to collect and record this rare species. Iâ€™m thrilled to get the opportunity to witness this one. The location has been recorded, and pending permissions, a sample will be making its way to Kew Gardens to be included in their genome sequencing projects and the national collection. Found by: Nicky Freeman Collected & record by: Iona Fraser @ashdownforage The species is characterised by its unusual stem, which is covered with short lateral branches. The branches often produce spherical slimeheads of translucentÂ conidiophoresÂ  on their swollen tips. The conidiophores produce conidia (asexualÂ spores) byÂ mitosis. Because the fungus can rely on eitherÂ sexualÂ orÂ asexualÂ modes of reproduction, fruit bodies sometimes have reduced or even missing caps. The unusual stems originate from black pea-sized structures calledÂ sclerotia. TheÂ anamorphicÂ form of the fungus, known asÂ TilachlidiopsisÂ racemosa, is missing the sexual stage of itsÂ life cycle. It can reproduce at relatively low temperatures, an adaptation believed to improve its ability to grow quickly and fruit on decomposing mushrooms. (Info via Wikimili) #allthingsfungi

Date: 2022-08-02 05:09:43
Caption: Hexagonia tenuis fungi is plentiful in the regenerating native forests at the base of the escarpment. These areas were originally cleared for farmland and mining. The returning forests are only approximately 50 years into the process of establishing themselves again and I'm always in awe of their regenerative power. It's hard not to amorphosize natural phenomena with the constraints our language puts upon us. Fungi networks are described like the internet, beehives are described like officeworkers, but we know this is a crude way to narrate the complexity, abstraction, mystery and full expression of nature. So I tread tentatively knowing these words that follow are inept, but to experience a regenerating forest is to be part of a continual homecoming. With each species of native flora and fauna that returns I personally am exalted but there is no fanfare, fireworks or roll call within the forest itself. Instead a palatable gathering of strength and an emerging tranquillity spreads as each species reestablishes itself within the dynamics of the forest family. Many of the photos in this gallery are from this regenerating forest and it is a joy to share the homecoming of species like this fungi with you. #mycology #mycologysociety #fungus #mycologyphotography #fungilover #fungiphotography #fungifanatic #fantasticfungi #fungiofinstagram #fungiownunder #fungihunter #fungiaustralia #fungifreaks #fungihunting #fungiidentification #fungikingdom #fungilove #fungiphotography #fungioftheday #mushroom #mushrooms #mushlove #mushroomphotography #mushroomsofinstagram #australianfungi #fungi #forestbathing #forestfinds #naturesbeauty #forestlovers #biodiversity

Date: 2021-01-16 18:40:24
Caption: In 2004 I was cultivating Reishi in Chile, studying from the only books available to me. I saved up, packed the essential, & took off to take @paulstamets course on cultivating gourmet and medicinal mushrooms. He was the author of those books, and the course was taught by him at @fungiperfecti in the PNW. It was incredible! Paul (who was still heavily stammering, btw @fantasticfungi) taught with passion and intense knowledge. This is where I first met somebody who loved fungi as much as I did. A brother. It truly was an awakening for me to understand that it was ok to be mushroom mad like Paul. I learnt to cultivate lion's mane (in the photo), shiitake, oysters, and more. Was taught how to make plug spawn, grain spawn, liquid spawn. I will never forget this transformational trip during my self-learning path in mycology. If a young woman from Chile did this in the late 90's/early 2000's, you all can do it now! Shout out to my awesome classmates @bigsilly49 @postcodeman @dameinpack @traddcotter #dontstop #thinkfungi #fungiaretheforce #mushrooms #thefutureisfungi #hongos #mycelium #micelio #rotnmould #rotnmold

Caption: "Magic Mushroom Cultivationâ€ by Steven Pollock M.D. (1977) is one of the legendary texts in the cultivation of "magic mushrooms". Many popular books were published in the US during the 70â€™s about the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., but this one stands out as one of the better known, particularly because in time Pollock was (incorrectly) associated with the cubensis strain "P envy". Pollock is also well known for finding and cultivating P. tampanensis, aka "Philosophers Stones". Psilocybe cubensis is one of the most cultivated mushrooms, and as a consequence of extensive collection, cultivation, breeding, and marketing ploys by various spore print sellers numerous â€œstrainsâ€ now exist. Unfortunately, much of the history of many of the older strains has been lost, or exist within obfuscated narratives from a variety of websites, with the person/s responsible having disappeared into history. Cailleux and Heim were the first to grow cultures of P. cubensis (as Stropharia cubensis), publishing their methods in 1957. During the late 1960â€™s and early 1970â€™s, those with access to scientific literature adapted laboratory techniques for the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., notably R.E. Brown and associates who published â€œThe Psychedelic Guide to the Preparation of the Eucharist in a Few of Its Many Guisesâ€ which was the first countercultural text to mention the cultivation of P. cubensis. Caption: You're so golden! ğŸ’› The Golden-scruffy Collybia (Cyptotrama asprata) is found all around the world. In Australia it's primarily found along the east coast. With a cushion-shaped mushroom cap that grows up to 2.7 centimetres in diameter, it's covered in bright yellow and orange protrusions that lose their vibrancy as the mushroom ages. Caption: Amanita muscaria, Fly Agaric, Amanitaceae. An introduced species to Australia, it is mycorrhizal with northern hemisphere conifers and hardwoods. Autumn and winter is when A. muscaria dominates the pine forests of Australia, though after the amount of rainfall we have had this summer, itâ€™s not unusual to have them popping up now, in the same way Lactarius deliciosus (saffron milk cap) has been plentiful this summer. I was puzzled when I found this, as it was in the middle of a Eucalyptus forest, though after looking around I found two Pinus radiata growing a little way away. Known around the world for a variety of reasons, it has been portrayed in folklore, prepared in the kitchen for food, as medicine, and as a hallucinogen (it contains ibotenic acid, a neurotoxin which converts to muscimol, a psychoactive compound, once digested). Amanita muscaria poses a serious threat to the biodiversity of native fungi in the Myrtle Beech forests of Victoria and Tasmania, where it has formed Mycohrriza with Nothofagus cunninghamii.

Caption: Fomitopsis betulina EN This species is a saprotroph or parasite specific to Betula spp. It can be found on logs, dead trees, but sometimes in live trees too, although it possibly only infects already decaying, trees. Like other brown rot fungi it degrades the carbohydrate fraction of lignocellulose but, in contrast to white rot fungi, leaves lignin in the form of cubical brown fragments. In Portugal I have only found them growing in high altitude in mountainous areas. PT Esta espÃ©cie Ã© um saprÃ³fito ou parasita especÃ­fico de espÃ©cies do gÃ©nero Betula. Caption: Happy #SlimeMoldSunday to Myxomycete lovers new and old! These amazing myxo fruiting bodies are Diachea leucopodia,Â one of my favorites because of theirÂ beautiful iridescence.Â  As with many slime molds, this species changes colors several times during its brief life cycle.Â  When they first arise from the white plasmodium, the fruiting bodies are white.Â  They then turn almost black, and as they mature and dry the peridium (outer covering of the spore-containing body) turns into these strikingly beautifulÂ iridescent blue, purple, and brown colors on a white stout stalk.Â  Although the individualÂ fruiting bodies are tiny, only 1-2mm tall, they can be easy to spot because they grow in dense and large clusters on leaves, grasses, and live and decaying plant material.Â  To see how tiny they are, see the second photo, which shows a few fruiting bodies on a twig with the tip of a fine point pen for scale. A little technical info for those of you who might be interested.Â  To photograph such tiny myxos with sharp detail, I use an extreme macro lens.Â  With such high magnifications, the depth of field (portion of the subject that is in sharp focus) is less than 0.05mm. To get a photo of the entire fruiting body in focus, I use a technique called focus stacking. My camera is mounted on a finely tuned rail, and the camera is moved in minuscule increments between each photo,Â so that the focal point changes with each photo.Â  Â For this photo, I took 138 individual images, which were then â€œstackedâ€ with specialized computer software that combines the most in-focus portions of each of the individual images into a composite image that shows everything in focus from front to back.

Caption: Dendrocollybia racemosa - Branched shanklet Not my find but a collaborative effort to collect and record this rare species. Iâ€™m thrilled to get the opportunity to witness this one. The location has been recorded, and pending permissions, a sample will be making its way to Kew Gardens to be included in their genome sequencing projects and the national collection. Found by: Nicky Freeman Collected & record by: Iona Fraser @ashdownforage The species is characterised by its unusual stem, which is covered with short lateral branches. The branches often produce spherical slimeheads of translucentÂ conidiophoresÂ  on their swollen tips. The conidiophores produce conidia (asexualÂ spores) byÂ mitosis. Because the fungus can rely on eitherÂ sexualÂ orÂ asexualÂ modes of reproduction, fruit bodies sometimes have reduced or even missing caps. The unusual stems originate from black pea-sized structures calledÂ sclerotia. TheÂ anamorphicÂ form of the fungus, known asÂ TilachlidiopsisÂ racemosa, is missing the sexual stage of itsÂ life cycle. It can reproduce at relatively low temperatures, an adaptation believed to improve its ability to grow quickly and fruit on decomposing mushrooms. (Info via Wikimili) #allthingsfungi

Caption: Amanita muscaria, Fly Agaric, Amanitaceae. An introduced species to Australia, it is mycorrhizal with northern hemisphere conifers and hardwoods. Autumn and winter is when A. muscaria dominates the pine forests of Australia, though after the amount of rainfall we have had this summer, itâ€™s not unusual to have them popping up now, in the same way Lactarius deliciosus (saffron milk cap) has been plentiful this summer. I was puzzled when I found this, as it was in the middle of a Eucalyptus forest, though after looking around I found two Pinus radiata growing a little way away. Known around the world for a variety of reasons, it has been portrayed in folklore, prepared in the kitchen for food, as medicine, and as a hallucinogen (it contains ibotenic acid, a neurotoxin which converts to muscimol, a psychoactive compound, once digested). Amanita muscaria poses a serious threat to the biodiversity of native fungi in the Myrtle Beech forests of Victoria and Tasmania, where it has formed Mycohrriza with Nothofagus cunninghamii.

Caption: "Magic Mushroom Cultivationâ€ by Steven Pollock M.D. (1977) is one of the legendary texts in the cultivation of "magic mushrooms". Many popular books were published in the US during the 70â€™s about the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., but this one stands out as one of the better known, particularly because in time Pollock was (incorrectly) associated with the cubensis strain "P envy". Pollock is also well known for finding and cultivating P. tampanensis, aka "Philosophers Stones". Psilocybe cubensis is one of the most cultivated mushrooms, and as a consequence of extensive collection, cultivation, breeding, and marketing ploys by various spore print sellers numerous â€œstrainsâ€ now exist. Unfortunately, much of the history of many of the older strains has been lost, or exist within obfuscated narratives from a variety of websites, with the person/s responsible having disappeared into history. Cailleux and Heim were the first to grow cultures of P. cubensis (as Stropharia cubensis), publishing their methods in 1957. During the late 1960â€™s and early 1970â€™s, those with access to scientific literature adapted laboratory techniques for the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., notably R.E. Brown and associates who published â€œThe Psychedelic Guide to the Preparation of the Eucharist in a Few of Its Many Guisesâ€ which was the first countercultural text to mention the cultivation of P. cubensis. Date: 2020-10-30 21:14:51
Caption: Photos by @Justin.Jin / Fungie, a dolphin that has made Dingle a world-famous tourist destination since the day he befriended a local fisherman 37 years ago, has not been seen near the Irish harbor town for weeks. Many people around the world are mourning the bottlenose dolphin that has chosen humans as his lifelong friends. I set out to sea to photograph Fungie in 2006. For days he was nowhere to be seen, and suddenly he leapt out of the water right next to my boat. It was challenging to capture the moment because I didn't know where he might appear and when. I jumped into the frigid water to swim with him, but he did not oblige. Our brief encounters touched me. I can understand the people in Dingle missing him dearly. Goodbye, Fungie. Follow photographer @Justin.Jin for more stories and pictures from around the world. #dingle #dinglepeninsula #swimfreefungie #fungie #fungiethedolphin

Caption: A critically endangered fungus - Tea-tree Fingers. This colony was only recently discovered by colleagues and is bigger than all the other previously known fruiting bodies combined. And it's the only colony within a National Park. The whacky thing is it feeds on another couple of specific species of fungi, so to conserve this fungus, we must conserve its hosts first. The other colonies are threatened by sand mining activity. #teatreefingers #rememberthewild #wildvictoria #VicOurNature #fungimap #endangered #SaveWesternportWoodlands

It can reproduce at relatively low temperatures, an adaptation believed to improve its ability to grow quickly and fruit on decomposing mushrooms. (Info via Wikimili) #allthingsfungi

Caption: Of more than a hundred compounds measured in the bloodstreams of thousands of individuals, the one most associated with the lowest rates of disease and death was an amino acid called ergothioneine. Higher blood levels were associated with lower risk of heart disease, stroke, and death from all causes put together over a period of more than 20 years. Ergothioneine was discovered more than a century ago, but it was ignored until recently, when researchers found that humans have a highly specific transporter protein in our bodies specifically designed to pull ergothioneine out of food and into body tissue. What are the best dietary sources of ergothioneine? It isnâ€™t made by plants or animalsâ€“â€“only fungi, like mushrooms and certain soil bacteria. Plants can suck some up from the soil and animals who eat the plants can similarly benefit, but the highest levels by far have been reported in mushrooms. Mushrooms and tempehâ€”a fungi-fermented soybean cakeâ€”are the only concentrated dietary sources. As mushrooms go, shiitake and oyster mushrooms have higher levels than white button mushrooms. However, just eating a cup a day of ordinary white mushrooms can double ergothioneine concentrations in the blood. Mushroom consumption is associated with a lower risk of cancer, driven mainly by lower breast cancer rates, as well as a lower risk of dying prematurely from all causes put together. Interventional trials have found, for example, that eating just a few mushrooms a day can improve immune function. How Not to Age is out now! Happiness (0.55)
Date: 2021-01-04 13:01:19
Caption: We must not continue down this path of indiscriminate war on microbes. ğŸ”¬ The soil microbes, and the beneficial microbes of our body, are the foundation of all life. In our misunderstanding and fear of specific microbes, we have launched an all out war on Nature. Bacteria, fungi, and viruses are critical to life on Earth. Antibiotics, pesticides and fungicides, sanitizers, etc are being used so injudiciously, that the very fabric of human and planetary health is at stake. We must learn the patience to discover the difference between friend and foe. As with all things in Nature, diversity is the key. Without diversity, the system collapses. The invisible microbes do not have a voice of their own - at least not in the traditional sense. But if we continue to ignore them, the microbial ecosystem will become so imbalanced that we will be forced to pay attention to their power. There is no life in a fully sterilized world. We must learn to live alongside these microbes, and acknowledge the significant role they play in the health of our planet. #microbes #invisible #tiny #microscopic #soilorganisms #organism #life #earth #motherearth #ecosystem #circleoflife #systemsthinking #systems #fungicides #pesticides
